properties.name: TestExpression
properties.description: You can describe a test by expressions and by the functions described below. Expression and logical operator The expression of a test comprises expressions. These expressions can be logically combined using brackets   ()   as well as logical operators. Logical operators available are: And and Xor Xor is the exclusive  Or , that is  true when one and only one of the combined expressions is true . It is also possible to use not to obtain the negative of an expression Comparison attribute and operator The expression of a test can be defined using various functions and comparison operators. Comparison operators are: = <> > < >= <= These comparison operators can be used to define an expression from the value of one of the MetaAttributes of the tested MetaClass. Fonction ItemCount() and comparison operator Comparison operators can also be used to define an expression from the ItemCount function. This function returns the number of objects found at the end of the MetaAssociationEnd or returned by the selector: ItemCount(LegSel) Where LegSel is a field representing a MetaAssociationEnd or a Selector. Operation<>   Returns  true  if at least one operation is connected. Use of a selector in the ItemCount() function of course requires that the selector starts from the currently tested object, or that this does not require an input object.Functions TrueForEach() and TrueForOne() These functions enable definition of an expression applying to an object or objects at the end of a MetaAssociationEnd or of a selector. TrueForEach returns  true  if the expression is true for all objects found at the end of the MetaAssociationEnd or returned by the selector. If no object is found or returned, this function returns  true . TrueForOne returns  true  if the expression is true for at least one of the objects found at the end of the MetaAssociationEnd or returned by the selector. If no object is found or returned, this function returns  true . TrueForEach(LegSel, Expression) TrueForOne(LegSel, Expression) Where LegSel is a field representing a MetaAssociationEnd or a Selector. Note here that when we use the TrueForEach and TrueForOne functions with a MetaAssociationEnd, it is possible to use in the expression : The link attributes and or The attributes of the object at the end of the linkIn the expression used by a TrueForEach or TrueForOne function, it is of course possible to use one of these two functions again so as to take a new MetaAssociationEnd or to trigger a new selector. In the implementation test properties dialog box, the tree presenting the MetaAssociationEnds and MetaAttributes enables navigation in depth of the metamodel. It is therefore possible to drag-and-drop one of the attributes of an object at the end of a MetaAssociationEnd. Other available functions ItemExist(LegSel, Object) Where LegSel is a field representing a MetaAssociationEnd or a Selector. This function returns  true  if the specified object is connected via the identifed MetaAssociationEnd or is present in the set of objects returned by the selector. Availabe(Object) This function returns  true  if the specified object exists.

properties.name: ResidualRiskComputingMode
properties.description: Residual risk calculation mode enables specification of how the residual risk value was obtained.residual risk = absolute risk - absolute risk*(global evaluation of controls 100)Global evaluation of controls can be:  - value 1 if no  evaluation is available. In this case, residual risk is equal to absolute risk.  - the prevention coefficient directly specified on the risk by the risks manager. This is the case if no other information is available on controls associated with the risk  - an average of the evaluation of each of the controls connected to the risk.Evaluation of each of the controls can be defined by: - global evaluation of control defined by the risks manager - or the average of control tests calculated from results of questionnaires sent to the different stakeholders to evaluate control efficiency.For each control, priority in the calculation is given to the most precise evaluation. - So, if an average of control tests derived from questionnaires is available, it is this that is taken into account. - If not, but there is a global evaluation of control specified by the risks manager, it is this that is taken into account. - If nothing is specified on the control, but the risk prevention coefficient has been specified by the risks manager, it is this value that is taken into account. - If the prevention coefficient has not been specified, value 1 is used.This calculation can be modified in the  Risk Level Residual Matrix  macro.

properties.name: RiskAvoidance
properties.description: Decision to avoid a risk after the analysis of its causes and consequences by modifying the strategy, the organisation or the techniques used.

properties.name: RiskReduction
properties.description: Decision to mitigate a risk using controls, or changes in the organization or the techniques used to reduce its likelihood or its negative consequence if the risk happens.

properties.name: RiskTransferSubcontractor
properties.description: Decision to transfer a risk to a sub-contractor more qualified to treat this type of risk.

properties.name: RiskInsurance
properties.description: The choice of insurance is a common form of transfer which can be combined with any other treatment decisions.

metaclass.name: OrgUnit
metaclass.description: An org-unit represents a person or a group of persons that intervenes in the enterprise business processes or information system. An org-unit can be internal or external to the enterprise.- An internal org-unit is an organizational element of the enterprise structure such as a department, a service, or a workstation. An internal org-unit is defined based on how detailed you require your view of the enterprise to be (cf org-unit-type). Example: financial management, sales management, marketing department, account manager.- An external entity is an organization that exchanges flows with the enterprise. Example: Customer, Supplier, Government Office.

properties.name: Transaction
properties.description: A transaction is a set of coordinated activities leading to a consistent, and verifiable outcome.

properties.name: Loop
properties.description: A loop is a process step that is repeated as long as a condition is true: - Do While: the condition is evaluated before the first execution. - Do Until: the condition is evaluated after the first execution. In this case, the process step is executed at least once.

properties.name: AdHoc
properties.description: Steps of an ad hoc process are not controlled or sequenced in a particular order. Theirperformance is determined by the performers of the process.

properties.name: Multiple
properties.description: The process step is repeated a number of times that is evaluated only once before it is performed. It can be repeated in parallel or sequentially.

enumValues.name: Sequential
enumValues.description: SequentialThe process step is repeated sequentially a number of times that is evaluated before it is performed.

enumValues.name: Parallel
enumValues.description: ParallelThe process step is repeated  in parallel a number of times that is evaluated before it is performed.

enumValues.name: No
enumValues.description: NoThe process step is not repeated a number of times that is evaluated before it is performed.

properties.name: Compensation
properties.description: A compensation defines the set of activities that are performed during the roll-back of a transaction to compensate for activities that were performed during the normal flow of the process.

properties.name: LoopCondition
properties.description: The loop execution condition represents the condition which is tested for each iteration to decide if the loop will be executed one more or not.

properties.name: OrganizationalProcessStatus
properties.description: Status of the organizational process under review: - Update in progress: the process is currently being updated -  Validation in progress: the process has been updated and is waiting to be validated - Validated: process description has been validated

properties.name: TaskType
properties.description: You can indicate the task type such as process call, send, receive, manual, business rule, script, service (the use of an IT-Service), or user task (with a GUI).

enumValues.name: Manual
enumValues.description: ManualA Manual task is a task that is expected to be performed without the aid of any business process execution engine or any application. An example of this could be a telephone technician installing a telephone at a customer location.

enumValues.name: Receive
enumValues.description: ReceiveA Receive task is a simple task that is designed to wait for a message to arrive from an external participant (relative to the process). Once the message has been received, the task is completed.

enumValues.name: Send
enumValues.description: SendA Send task is a simple task that is designed to send a message to an external participant (relative to the process). Once the Message has been sent, the task is completed.

enumValues.name: BusinessRule
enumValues.description: Business RuleA Business Rule task provides a mechanism for the process to provide input to a business rules engine and to get the output of calculations that the business rules engine might provide.

enumValues.name: Script
enumValues.description: ScriptA Script task is executed by a process engine. The modeler or implementer defines a script in a language that the engine can interpret. When the task is ready to start, the engine will execute the script. When the script is completed, the task will also be completed.

enumValues.name: User
enumValues.description: UserA User task is a typical workflow task where a human performer performs the task with the assistance of a software application (GUI). It can be scheduled through a task list manager of some sort.

enumValues.name: IT_ServiceCall
enumValues.description: IT-Service CallAn IT-Service Call task is a task that uses some sort of service, which could be a web service or an automated application.

enumValues.name: SystemProcessCall
enumValues.description: System Process CallA  System Process Call task is a task that is used to call another process from within the first process.

properties.name: InputLogic
properties.description: Defines input logic: - junction means that processing continues as soon as one of the input messages or triggering sequence flows is available - synchronisation means processing only continues when all input messages or expected sequence flows become available
